  "timeframe": "1D",
  "market_context": "Oil daily chart in a downtrend showing repeated swing highs that were never swept and a relevant low with significant separation that eventually gets traded into, followed by an expansion higher.",
  "key_observation": "The chart is building stacked failure swings on the highs (untouched liquidity) while the lows show relevant levels with separation; trading short away from failure swings is unreliable because that stacked liquidity is the draw.",
  "analysis_steps": [
    "Step 1: Identify a relevant low by noting significant separation between it and the previous low, marking it as a potential reaction level.",
    "Step 2: Observe that consolidation follows, then speed through to highlight that the daily chart is repeatedly building failure swings on the highs.",
    "Step 3: Point out the stacked highs as failure swings and conclude they should not be trusted as short entry levels because they remain as untouched liquidity above.",
    "Step 4: Confirm a relevant high above the stack and identify the relevant low below as the location to look for a reversal.",
    "Step 5: After price finally hits the relevant low, identify it as a reversal area drawing back toward the relevant highs (the stacked failure-swing liquidity).",
    "Step 6: Note that even after expansion higher, trading away from this point is undesirable because a nearby failure-swing high (a fair value gap acting as a lower-time-frame high) is still left above."
  ],
  "outcome": null,
  "lessons": "Failure swings represent stacked, unswept liquidity that becomes the draw on price; never trade away from failure swings on the stop-loss side. Prefer setups where high-resistance liquidity protects the stop and failure swings sit on the target side.",
